FOODBORNE ILLNESS - JAPAN (02): (TOKYO AREA) NORI, NOROVIRUS
************************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

[1]
Date: Wed 1 Mar 2017
Source: EpiCore Global Surveillance Project [edited]


According to Tokyo Metropolitan Government, the vehicle of the foodborne illness, which affected more than 1000 teachers and students of 7 primary schools in Tachikawa city, [western part of Tokyo Metropolis], on 17 Feb 2017, was determined as shredded seaweed (kizami nori in Japanese) that was produced by a company in Osaka. The seaweed was served at lunch on 16 Feb 2017. Molecular biological tests revealed that the genotypes of the norovirus from one of the patients and that from the seaweed stored at a shop was matched. The Osaka city health department has already been informed of the findings.

According to Tokyo Metropolitan Government, there were 2 similar foodborne disease outbreaks occurred in Gobou city, Wakayama [prefecture] in late January [2017] and Kodaira city, [western part of Tokyo Metropolis], from [23-27 Feb 2017] the latter of which affected about 90 students and teachers who developed vomiting and diarrhea. In both settings, the identical seaweeds produced by the same company were served.
(http://www3.nhk.or.jp/news/html/20170228/k10010893041000.html; in Japanese)

--
Communicated by:
EpiCore Surveillance Project member
