******
[2]
Date: Mon 27 Feb 2017
Source: Nihon Keizai Shinbun web version (25 Feb 2017 13:57 JST) [in Japanese, trans., edited]
http://www.nikkei.com/article/DGXLZO13381780V20C17A2CN0000/ and
Asahi Shinbun digital (24 Feb 2017 19:45 JST) [in Japanese, trans., edited]
http://www.asahi.com/articles/ASK2S6FB9K2SUTIL05N.html


On 24 Feb 2017, the Tokyo metropolitan government concluded that the food poisoning outbreak of 7 elementary schools in Tachikawa City was caused by the meal prepared by a school lunch center and ordered the center not to supply meals for 3 days. Causative foods remain unclear. Tachikawa City suspended meals delivered by the center to 13 schools where the center had delivered meals, until the end of March [2017].

According to Tachikawa City, students, teachers and staff with vomiting and abdominal pain increased to 1098 persons at noon of 24 Feb 2017. 9 students were hospitalized and all have been discharged. Students of the 13 schools are asked to bring lunch boxes until the end of March 2017.

In the investigations by the Tokyo metropolitan government, norovirus was detected in feces samples from 40 persons. Students and so on contracted the disease after eating the same meal and presented syndromes like food poisoning since late-evening of 17 Feb 2017 although norovirus was not detected in samples from cooks nor from stored foods.

Food poisoning outbreaks with about 1000 cases in Tokyo had not occurred since 1978, when that occurred in Akigawa City (now part of Akiruno City [western part of Tokyo Metropolis]).

--
Communicated by:
EpiCore Global Surveillance Project
<promed@promedmail.org>

*****
[3]
Date: Fri 24 Feb 2017
Source: NHK News Web (24 Feb 2017 20:02 JST) [in Japanese, trans., edited]
http://www3.nhk.or.jp/news/html/20170224/k10010889221000.html


Tokyo Metropolitan Government announced that they found norovirus from feces of 40 students who had symptoms.

The Government has determined that the virus was likely the cause of the outbreak. The Government ordered temporary suspension of the cooking facility for 3 days, starting from 24 Feb 2017.

Since [17 Feb 2017], a total of 1098 people, including 1019 students and 79 teachers of 7 primary schools in Tachikawa city had nausea, stomach ache, vomiting, and diarrhea, of which 9 had temporarily been hospitalized.

--
Communicated by:
EpiCore Surveillance Project member
Dr Masaki Ota
Research Institute of Tuberculosis
Tokyo
Japan

